# Engineering Rules

You must follow these rules when generating or modifying code:

1. Prefer simple solutions.
2. Do not duplicate code. Check for existing utilities, helpers, services, components, or patterns before adding new logic.
3. Only change what was requested, plus changes that are clearly necessary for correctness and directly related.
4. For bug fixes, stay within the current implementation and existing patterns first.
5. Do not introduce new frameworks, patterns, or technologies unless the current approach has been reasonably exhausted.
6. If you replace an old implementation with a new one, remove the old logic so only one source of truth remains.
7. Keep the codebase clean, organized, and consistent with existing structure.
8. Avoid adding one-off scripts or throwaway files unless there is no cleaner option.
9. Keep files focused. Refactor when a file exceeds roughly 200–300 lines.
10. Use standard architectural patterns and design patterns only when they clearly improve clarity or maintainability.
11. Never overwrite or modify .env files without explicit confirmation.
